The inventor of the World Wide Web intends to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, has created a startup that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this legendary tech character, Inrupt, is a company leveraging Berners-Lee’s open source platform, Solid.
This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly stated that Inrupt’s underlying intention is to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data warehouse,” or POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
What is unique about the personal online data warehouse is that it is exclusively up to the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to company CEO John Bruce, is to provide the right resources, processes and competencies to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently comprised of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some in-house programmers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology creators around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a total change in which all their business models are turned upside down overnight.
“We’re not asking for permission.”
In a post on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to create commercial power and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new Web created with Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over Internet neutrality.
Even as he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Tribute to the clergyman decorated with the Victoria Cross in the First Great War
The only Church of England clergyman to receive the Victoria Cross during the First Great War as a combatant was honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant-Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann won the award on September 29, 1918 with the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew he received the highest British military honor.
His two grandchildren unveiled a commemorative plaque at a stop in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of them, Michael Vann, said it was "brilliantly symbolic" that the plaque had been presented exactly 100 years after the achievement that gave the decoration to his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very thick fog and under closed fire of portable weapons and machine guns."
He then rushed to the line of fire and, "with the greatest courage," led the line forward before attacking a cannon alone and shooting down three soldiers from the detachment.
Lieutenant-Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I could never match, but also a lesson in humility.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, deposited a wreath of flowers after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was “very honored to participate in the parade” and added that “the courage of a genuine hero is being demonstrated through the support that will be given by many people.”
