Olympic diver Tom Daley said he grew up feeling inferior to everyone because of his sexuality, but that this gave him motivation to become a success.
The 24-year-old athlete said he didn’t realize until he entered high school that “not everyone is like me.”
In an interview with Radio 4's first Desert Island Discs presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had spoken out in favor of gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also claimed that becoming a father made him worry less about winning the Olympics.
The show's longtime regular host, Kirsty Young, took a several-month break due to illness.
Appearing as an outcast on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt "inferior" to everyone else because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and girls."
To this day, this impression of feeling smaller and different has been the real motive that has given me the power and strength to achieve success.
His goal was to prove that he was “someone,” he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they discovered their sexuality sooner or later.
The double Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent LGBT activist and has used his participation in this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
According to him, he manifested himself because he was happy to be able to live openly without consequences and intended to give "hope" to others.
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "has taken me by surprise."
Daley married the 20-year-old Oscar winner last year, though he said age difference was never a problem.
"When we go through so much when we're so young" - his first Olympics appearance was at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said, it's hard to find someone of the same age who has gone through similar ups and downs.
The couple had a son last year in June, named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley claimed that "their whole outlook" had changed.
“If you had asked me last year, all that mattered was to win a gold medal,” he said.
"But you know, there are bigger things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept the fact that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets for the 2012 London games because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be here to be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
"I was holding him out of hand when he stopped breathing and it was only when he really stopped breathing and died that I finally recognized that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
"I was fully aware that it was what I had dreamed of all my life: diving in front of a crowd of compatriots at the Olympic Games ... there was no better feeling," he said.
All this was also the inspiration for her first song choice - Proud, by Heather Small - with which she had identified herself during the preparation for the Olympics, and which still gives her chicken skin.
