German warship once again delayed
The latest German navy frigate should have entered service in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships. However, it will be necessary to wait at least until next year, due to systems prone to breakdowns and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the command ship of the brand new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to Die Zeit newspaper, which cited a military spokesman.
The vessel should have joined the navy in 2014, but disturbing post-delivery problems undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class that the navy had ordered in 2007 will serve to replace the aged Bremen class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, as well as a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenance, which would allow the latest frigates to be sent on missions with a maximum duration of two years away from the ports of origin.
However, the continued delays have meant that with state-of-the-art warships, seen as a way for Germany to project power across borders, they will already be out of date when they enter service, Die Zeit reports.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German navy refused to put it into service, having returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyards in Hamburg.
This was the first time the navy had returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cite a number of crucial "hardware and software defects" that would render the warship useless if used in a combat mission.
The software deficiencies were particularly important, as the Baden-Württemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half the contingent needed on the oldest Bremen-class frigates.
It was also known that the vessel is excessively heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the navy’s ability to install additional functionality in the future.
The 7,000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is thought to be twice the weight of similar-class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware flaws, the cost of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said that this will have reached a staggering 3.1 billion euros, an increase from the 2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems plaguing the latest frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, leader of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used.
He said the problem has grown exponentially over time, as older ships have been put out of service without existing vessels to replace them.
In the end, he lamented that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates were able to join the navy.
National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
Further investigations are underway on a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations throughout the property to track the bats’ activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors on a territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland farming, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development work that affect dormitories and make habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning also pose a threat, along with fly papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly conduct studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
It has also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, at the Threave estate at Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The property’s director, David Thompson, says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there is still a lot about bats that we don’t know, so the work we do here and on the other properties will help us know more about what they need to flourish.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance on the properties, as the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dorm could lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don’t know how their populations are avenging.”
