Brexit: UK 'would regret forever' losing automakers
The UK would “repent forever” if it lost its status as a world leader in car manufacturing after Brexit, Business Secretary Greg Clark said.
Clark also said that Toyota in the UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, it would temporarily stop production at its plant in Burnaston near Derby.
“We need a deal,” Mr. Clark said.
The Japanese manufacturer said the impact of border delays in the event of a no-deal Brexit could lead to job losses.
The Burnaston plant, which produces Toyota’s Auris and Avensis models, produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My perspective is that if Britain leaves the EU disorderly at the end of March, we will see production stoppages at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s chief executive officer in Burnaston.
Other automakers in the UK have expressed concerns about leaving the EU without an agreement on the functioning of cross-border transactions, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover.
BMW, for example, said it would shut down its Minis factory in Oxford for a month after Brexit.
The main concerns concern what manufacturers say are supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line is managed on a “just-in-time” basis, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in both the UK and the EU for custom-made cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be disruptions at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to maintain more than one day of stock at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, so production would have to stop.
Clark said Theresa May’s “Chequers Plan” for future relations with the EU was “precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks.”
“We have to have an agreement, we want to have the best deal that allows, as I said, not only the current success, but also the seizing by us of this opportunity,” he told BBC Radio 4’s Today program.
“Evidence not only from Toyota but also from other manufacturers indicates that we absolutely need to be able to continue what has been a highly successful supply chain set.”
Although it was not able to give an estimate of the downtime, Toyota said that in the long run the increased costs would reduce the factory’s competitiveness and could sooner or later lead to job losses.
Peter Tsouvallaris, who worked at the Burnaston factory for 24 years and coordinates the Unite union there, said that its members are increasingly concerned: "In my experience, if they are lost, these jobs will never come back.
A government spokesman said: “We have put forward a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.”
