The move is seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign to attract the younger electorate, with promises to make more affordable housing available and tax higher incomes.
The increase in the stamp tax will affect people and businesses that are not taxed in the UK, with the additional revenue boosting the government’s campaign to offer a roof to the homeless.
The surcharge – added to the current stamp tax, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and lease purchases – could amount to three percent.
