The new policy comes weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a stamp tax cut to help young people acquire their first home.
He accused the big construction companies of keeping property prices high by hoarding unused land, demanding that Mrs May abandon quotas on affordable housing to solve the "housing misfortune" in Britain.
Mr. Corbyn announced a so-called set of proposals for housing reform, including rent controls and the end of evictions "without justification".
It also wants to give the municipalities extended powers for the construction of new houses.
May said: “Last year I stated that I would dedicate my mandate to restoring the British dream that living conditions should be improved for every new generation.
And that means solving the problem of our real estate market.
Britain will always be open to people who want to live, work and build their lives here.
However, it is not certain that it is as easy to buy a home for people living outside the UK and for foreign companies as it is for British resident workers.
