Europe wins Ryder Cup in Paris
The European National Team beats the U.S. and wins the 2018 Ryder Cup with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National on the outskirts of Paris, France.
The U.S. has now accumulated six consecutive losses on European soil since the last time they won the Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe is once again crowned victorious after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
U.S. star Phil Mickelson, who proved to have serious difficulties during most of the tournament, threw the starting tee into the water at hole 16, par 3, giving the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined in all his rounds, becoming 1 of the 4 players to get 5-0-0 since the current tournament format began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked player in the European team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world’s top-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2 and 1 to England’s Ian Poulter in what may have been his last Ryder Cup appearance.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, Spaniard Sergio Garcia became the most awarded European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit to cry, but today I couldn’t contain myself.
It's been a tough year.
I can't help but thank Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we won the cup.
It was all a team effort and I’m happy to have been able to help,” said an emotional Garcia after Europe’s victory.
Pass the word to his compatriot Jon Rham who defeated the American golf legend, Tiger Woods, by 2&1 in singulars on Sunday.
“It’s impossible to describe how proud I am to have defeated Tiger Woods, and I grew up watching him play,” said Rahm, 23.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 Ryder Cup record.
