With the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau who had a high-caliber performance throughout the tournament, the remaining U.S. national team members struggled to get to the fairway.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance. "I'm proud of them. They fought.
This morning, we managed to put some fear into Europe.
We fought.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players were excellent.
We will reorganize and I will collaborate with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Commission to move forward.
I like many of these 12 players and am proud to be their captain.
I have to take my hat off the other team.
They were better."
Up-to-date information on the Red Tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower proliferation of spots were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide spot stretches about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also sighted in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded along or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations along or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations along or off the coast.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwestern region of Florida.
